  "notes": "Built from the 1930s Pipers' Guild treble pipe in D proportions supplied by the user. This snapshot uses a 305 mm body as the initial rough-cut length within the stated 29-31 cm finished range, with the understanding that a historical maker would cut slightly long and trim the foot back until all-holes-closed settled on D. Bore is modeled at 18.5 mm with slight natural taper toward the head, and outer diameter is held around 24 mm to stay inside the 22-25 mm historical comfort range. The windway/window geometry is not explicitly modeled by this app; use the historical values outside the physics model: top to window center about 25 mm, window about 6 mm by 5 mm, sloped mouthpiece, and a thinned knife-edge lip. Hole spacings here are translated directly from the Guild's distances measured from the labium downward: H1 C# 115 mm, H2 B 135 mm, H3 A 158 mm, H4 G 185 mm, H5 F# 208 mm, H6 E 232 mm, thumb D' 95 mm on the back. Hole diameters are left at the recommended pilot sizes so this file should be treated as a rough-cut starting point for iterative enlargement and trimming, not as a final acoustically optimized build."
